SIMPLE: excavate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excavate
<hw>Ex"ca*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Excavated</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Excavating</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>excavatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>excavare</ets> to excavate;
<ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>cavare</ets> to make hollow, <ets>cavus</ets>
hollow. See <er>Cave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hollow out; to
form cavity or hole in; to make hollow by cutting, scooping, or digging;
<as>as, to <ex>excavate</ex> a ball; to <ex>excavate</ex> the
earth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form by hollowing; to shape, as a cavity, or
anything that is hollow; <as>as, to <ex>excavate</ex> a canoe, a cellar,
a channel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>To dig out and remove, as
earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The material <qex>excavated</qex> was usually sand.</q>
<rj><qau>E. L. Corthell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Excavating pump</b></col>, <cd>a kind of dredging
apparatus for excavating under water, in which silt and loose material
mixed with water are drawn up by a pump.</cd>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excavation</ent>⟦br⟧
